This paper is likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category as it focuses on improving the security of a software ecosystem by identifying least privilege violation. It also introduces a novel technique for detecting and ranking software based on the severity of the violation. 

It could also belong to cs.SE (Software Engineering) as it proposes a new technique for categorizing software based on its functionality. 

cs.PL (Programming Languages) is another possible sub-category as the paper discusses the principle of least privilege, which is a concept often discussed in programming language design. 

cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is a less likely sub-category, but it could be relevant as the paper discusses how market operators can incentivize software developers to adhere to the principle of least privilege. 

Finally, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is a less likely sub-category, but it could be relevant as the paper uses empirical data to evaluate the effectiveness of the proposed technique.
